					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						too much for a good fellow.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						( Animus est entelechia. Ingenium, 
						( quinta essentia.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Mind is actualization. Genius, the fifth essence.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nihil sublimatu[m] (
						satis, aut rectificatum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Nothing is ever elevated or rectified enough.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Oratio, quasi serena animi lux.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Speech is as if a serene light of the soul. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nullus Oratorum adhuc, aut Poetaru[m] Axiophilo satisfecit. Qui esse voluit non
						mod&ograve; ratione, arte, virtute plenior: sed etiam rotundior, fluentior, penetrantior:
						sed vita, spirituq[ue] animosior. Vt nihil viuidius, aut valentius.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Axiophilus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				No orator or poet has yet satisfied Axiophilus. He who wanted not only to be fuller of reason, art, and virtue, <!--JG: Could the 'qui' refer to Axiophilus instead of being impersonal (as is 'someone') here?-->
				but also more well-rounded, more fluent, more penetrating. But he is stronger than life or spirit. Just as nothing is more lively or powerful. <!-- CG: Unclear on 'vita spirituque' etc. --> <!--JG: Perhaps stronger 'in life and spirit', although your translation, because of comp. + abl. makes sense.-->			
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						The best Orators, or Poets haue sumthing harsh, or cowld. All woold be
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="270">
					<marginalia_text>
						illuminate, current, &amp; full of life.
						As vigorous, as the spirit of Wine;
						or the most soueraine Aqua Vita[e].
						No Cordiall, so mightily cordiall.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
		</marginalia>
		
